{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"25a01021-ca49-4580-93be-bac4f8119512","content":"The project doesn't exist yet at that path, but here's how to configure `mcp.json` for a C# MCP server using **stdio** transport (the standard for VS Code agent mode):\n\nCreate `.vscode/mcp.json` in your workspace:\n\n```json\n{\n  \"servers\": {\n    \"my-mcp-server\": {\n      \"type\": \"stdio\",\n      \"command\": \"dotnet\",\n      \"args\": [\"run\", \"--project\", \"src/MyMcpServer/MyMcpServer.csproj\"]\n    }\n  }\n}\n```\n\n**Key points:**\n\n- **`type: \"stdio\"`** — Copilot communicates with your server over stdin/stdout.\n- Your C# server must read JSON-RPC messages from stdin and write responses to stdout (use a library like `ModelContextProtocol` / `Microsoft.Extensions.AI`).\n- **Don't write logs to stdout** — use stderr instead, or they'll corrupt the protocol stream.\n- For a published build, swap the command to `\"command\": \"dotnet\", \"args\": [\"path/to/MyMcpServer.dll\"]` for faster startup.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"e16a6d22-d821-4765-93c1-4268deb2b470","outputTokens":274,"requestId":"7FD0:B328E:4428C54:4AC0D70:69F15B2F"},"id":"ef00b5d6-7363-46ec-a226-36e7cf0d3907","timestamp":"2026-04-29T01:13:29.394Z","parentId":"ea51699c-b94b-4191-a66b-a96ad5577f73"}
